### Surviving aircraft

Despite their workhorse origins and the brutal nature of military training, a truly remarkable number of Stearmans have managed to cling to existence. They persist in flying condition across the globe, a testament to their rugged design and, perhaps, humanity's inexplicable sentimentality. The type remains a perennially popular sport plane and [warbird](/Warbird), resurrected and maintained by enthusiasts who clearly enjoy the anachronism of open cockpits and biplane wings.

#### Argentina

A particularly well-preserved [Argentine Naval Aviation](/Argentine_Navy) N2S-5 still graces the skies, a flying relic.

*   **308** – An N2S-5, remarkably airworthy, is housed at the Argentine Naval Aviation Museum in [Bahía Blanca, Buenos Aires](/Bah%C3%ADa_Blanca,_Buenos_Aires). It continues to defy entropy.

#### Australia

The vastness of Australia seems to have provided ample space for several Stearmans to thrive.

*   **75-6488** – A B75N1, registered as VH-EYC, remains airworthy, currently under the ownership of Steven Bradley in South Australia 5134.
*   **75-7462** – Another B75N1, registered as VH-PWS, is airworthy and owned by Michael Murphy of the Royal Aero Club of Victoria.
*   **75-8314** – An E75, registered as VH-USE, is airworthy and owned by Raalin, located in Western Australia 6208.

#### Austria

Even in the heart of Europe, the Stearman found a home, proving that its charm, or utility, transcends continents.

*   **75-2606** – Registered as OE-CBM, this aircraft is airworthy.
*   **75-5032** – A PT-17, registered as OE-AMM, is airworthy and prominently displayed at [Hangar-7](/Hangar-7) in [Salzburg](/Salzburg).

#### Brazil

Brazil, a former operator, also preserves examples of its past aerial acquisitions.

*   **K-132** – An A75L3, now a static display at the [Museu Aeroespacial](/Museu_Aeroespacial) in [Rio de Janeiro](/Rio_de_Janeiro).
*   **K-210** – An A76C3, also on static display at the Museu Aeroespacial in Rio de Janeiro.
*   **38010** – An N2S-3, on display at the [TAM Museum](/TAM_Museum) in [São Carlos, São Paulo](/S%C3%A3o_Carlos).

#### Canada

Canada, a wartime operator through [Lend-Lease](/Lend-Lease), has also diligently maintained a fleet of these venerable trainers.

*   **41-8621** – A PT-17, airworthy and a cherished part of the collection at the [Canadian Warplane Heritage Museum](/Canadian_Warplane_Heritage_Museum) in [Hamilton, Ontario](/Hamilton,_Ontario).
*   **42-17456** – A PT-13D, owned by Daniel Jones of Lacombe, Alberta, and still airworthy.
*   **5284** – An N2S-3, currently undergoing restoration to airworthy condition with Daniel Jones of [Lacombe, Alberta](/Lacombe,_Alberta).
*   **5293** – An N2S-3, owned by J. Kurtin of [Collingwood, Ontario](/Collingwood,_Ontario).
*   **30083** – An N2S-4, proudly on display at the [Reynolds-Alberta Museum](/Reynolds-Alberta_Museum) in [Wetaskiwin, Alberta](/Wetaskiwin,_Alberta).
*   **61105** – An N2S-5, under the care of Bruce Bond of [Sarnia, Ontario](/Sarnia,_Ontario).
*   **75-3498** – A PT-17, airworthy and operated by Great River Aviation Ltd. of [Whitehorse, Yukon](/Whitehorse,_Yukon), trading as Klondike Airways.
*   A PT-17 is also airworthy at the Canadian Aviation Museum in [Windsor, Ontario](/Windsor,_Ontario).

#### Colombia

Colombia also boasts a pair of airworthy PT-17s, continuing their legacy.

*   **FAC-62** – A PT-17, reported as airworthy.
*   **FAC-1995** – Another PT-17, also reported as airworthy.

#### Iceland

An unexpected home for a Stearman, proving their resilience even in harsh climates.

*   **T5-1556** – A PT-17, airworthy with Erling Pétur Erlingsson in [Hafnarfjörður, Capital Region](/Hafnarfj%C3%B6r%C3%B0ur). This particular aircraft holds the distinction of being the oldest airplane in Iceland, having been delivered to the country in 1941 by the aircraft carrier USS Wasp, only to suffer damage in an accident in 1943. A survivor, indeed.

#### Indonesia

Indonesia also preserves a piece of this aviation history.

*   A PT-13D is on display at [Dirgantara Mandala Museum](/Dirgantara_Mandala_Museum) in [Yogyakarta](/Yogyakarta). The aircraft is notable for being painted in [Taloa Academy of Aeronautics](/Transocean_Air_Lines) livery.

#### Israel

The [Israeli Air Force Museum](/Israeli_Air_Force_Museum) houses one of the PT-17s purchased during its formative years.

*   **2752** – A PT-17, airworthy and on display at the [Israeli Air Force Museum](/Israeli_Air_Force_Museum) in [Hatzerim](/Hatzerim_Airbase).

#### Mexico

Mexico's military aviation history includes a Stearman on static display.

*   **EPS-6084** – A PT-17, on static display at the Museo Militar de Aviación in [Santa Lucía, Zumpango](/Santa_Luc%C3%ADa,_Zumpango).

#### Netherlands

The lowlands of the Netherlands also host several airworthy examples, diligently maintained.

*   **75-7027** – A PT-13B, airworthy and registered as PH-TOX, owned by Joe Brewer and based at [Oostwold Airport](/Oostwold_Airport).
*   **75-7213** – An N2S-3, airworthy and registered as N9912H, owned by the Nordsiek family and based at [Breda International Airport](/Breda_International_Airport).
*   **75-5864** – A PT-13D Kaydet, airworthy and registered as N1944S, based at [Texel International Airport](/Texel_International_Airport).

#### New Zealand

