#### Peru

Peru also maintains a Stearman for historical preservation.

*   A PT-17 is on display at the Instituto de Estudios Históricos Aeroespaciales del Perú, Miraflores, Lima.

#### Spain

Spain, too, has a few examples preserved for posterity.

*   A PT-13 is on display at the Fundación Infante de Orleans in [Cuatro Vientos, Madrid](/Cuatro_Vientos).
*   A PT-17 is also on display at the Fundación Infante de Orleans in Cuatro Vientos, Madrid.

#### Switzerland

High in the Alps, a Stearman continues to fly, a testament to its enduring design.

*   **75-5436** – A PT-13D, airworthy and registered as HB-RBG, based at the Fliegermuseum [Altenrhein](/Altenrhein). This aircraft, built in 1943, was restored to airworthiness in 1989 after sustaining considerable damage during an emergency landing in the grounds of the [Stadler Rail](/Stadler_Rail) factory in Altenrhein due to engine failure. A rather dramatic return to service.

#### Taiwan

Taiwan's aviation heritage includes a static display Stearman.

*   A PT-17 is on static display at the Aviation Education Exhibition Hall in [Gangshan District, Kaohsiung City](/Gangshan_District).

#### United States

Unsurprisingly, the country of its origin, the [United States](/United_States), boasts the largest number of surviving Stearmans, both airworthy and on display in various museums. It seems even Americans can be sentimental.

*   The original **Model 70** prototype is airworthy and preserved at the [Western Antique Aeroplane & Automobile Museum](/Western_Antique_Aeroplane_%26_Automobile_Museum) in [Hood River, Oregon](/Hood_River,_Oregon).
